<dl id="n09152h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09152h">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09152h"> 152(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> speak sub / apology <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n09152h"><li>FW 189.08 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n09152h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n09152h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n09152h">MS BL 47471b-68v</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:383 <a name="g21d" href="../../ff/fdra/gda.htm#g21d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/g21d.htm#n09152h">Draft: I.7&sect;2.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Fancy a mother so anxious to say &ldquo;please&rdquo; to her child that she calls him &ldquo;Father&rdquo; as an equivalent for &ldquo;please,&rdquo; then <mark>puts it all in the subjunctive mood to soften off her maternal request</mark> for some small service he renders her. <small> Dan Crawford, <a name="BTLG1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BTLG1"><cite title="source">Back to the Long Grass</cite></a> (1923) 108</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
